<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1734,2013]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1950,1976]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species was previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[865,1013,1950,1976]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[1060,1199,1950,1977]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont (1991)</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dawah, H. A. &amp; Abdullah, M. A." pageId="26" pageNumber="27" pagination="373 - 396" refId="ref31297" refString="Dawah, H. A. &amp; Abdullah, M. A. (2009) The Muscidae (Diptera: Brachycera: Muscomorpha) of south-western Saudi Arabia. Fauna of Arabia, 24, 373 - 396." type="journal article" year="2009">Dawah &amp; Abdullah (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. It was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[490,543,1986,2012]" name="Italy" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Italy</collectingCountry>
. It was recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[795,863,1986,2012]" name="Oman" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Oman</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[905,1042,1986,2013]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont (1991)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,150,393]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,433,150,176]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Biological remarks.</emphasis>
This species is a well-known pest and is commonly known as “Sorghum Shootfly”. It is reported to be reared from 40 graminaceous host species, but sorghum is the main host for this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[1304,1424,186,212]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont 1991</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Deeming, J. C." box="[151,338,222,248]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="133 - 190" refId="ref31515" refString="Deeming, J. C. (1971) Some species of Atherigona Rondani (Diptera: Muscidae) from Northern Nigeria, with special reference to those injurious to cereal crops. Bulletin of Entomological Research, 61, 133 - 190. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0007485300057527" type="journal article" year="1971">Deeming (1971)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[397,546,222,249]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="27 - 102" refId="ref34848" refString="Pont, A. C. (1973 b) A review of the Oriental species of Atherigona Rondani (Diptera, Muscidae) of economic importance. In: Jotwani, M. G. &amp; Young, R. W. (Eds.), Control of Sorghum Shoot Fly. Oxford and IBH Publishing Co., New Delhi, pp. 27 - 102." type="book chapter" year="1973">Pont (1973b)</bibRefCitation>
have fully discussed the biology of this economically important pest. Larvae pupate in the plant or the soil, and the life cycle takes 2–3 weeks, depending on the temperature and humidity. This species is reported to have 15 generations a year in 
<collectingCountry box="[722,821,294,320]" name="Pakistan" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
. The eggs, larvae and pupae of this species are attacked by a few species of parasitoids (
<bibRefCitation author="Skidmore, P." box="[515,693,330,357]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refId="ref36277" refString="Skidmore, P. (1985) The Biology of the Muscidae of the World. Series Entomologica 29. Dr. W. Junk Publishers, Dordrecht, 550 pp." type="book" year="1985">Skidmore 1985</bibRefCitation>
). Prior to 1971 it was commonly referred to as 
<taxonomicName authority="van Emden" authorityName="van Emden" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Atherigona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="indica" subSpecies="infuscata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Atherigona indica infuscata</emphasis>
van Emden
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Rondani." authorityName="Rondani." box="[442,836,366,392]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Atherigona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="varia" subSpecies="soccata">
<emphasis box="[442,727,366,392]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Atherigona varia soccata</emphasis>
Rondani.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
